@startuml rule-drift
!theme plain
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
title Rule Drift — How Inconsistency Emerges Over Time

rectangle "Sprint 10: Initial Settlement" #E8F5E9 {
    card "Service.sellStockWithSettlement()" as s10_svc {
        card "checks: isSettled()" as s10_check
    }
    note right: Service is the **only** place\nwith settlement logic. No drift possible.
}

rectangle "Sprint 12: Reservation Feature" #E3F2FD {
    card "Service.sellStockWithSettlement()" as s12_svc {
        card "checks: isSettled() && !isReserved()" as s12_check
    }
    card "Lot.isAvailableForSale()" as s12_lot {
        card "isSettled(asOf)" as s12_lot_body #FFCDD2
    }
    note right of s12_lot
      Added by **Developer B** who
      copied the settlement check
      but missed the reservation flag.
    end note
}

rectangle "Sprint 14: New Endpoints" #FFF3E0 {
    card "Service.getEligibleSharesCount()" as s14_query {
        card "delegates to holding.getEligibleShares()" as s14_delegate
    }
    card "Holding.getEligibleShares()" as s14_holding {
        card "Σ lot.availableShares(asOf)" as s14_sum
    }
    s14_delegate --> s14_sum
    s14_sum --> s12_lot_body : uses flawed method

    note right of s14_query
      **Developer C** assumes
      domain methods are authoritative.
      They are not — they drift.
    end note
}

s10_svc -[hidden]down-> s12_svc
s12_svc -[hidden]down-> s14_query

note bottom
  **Timeline of drift:**
  Sprint 10: One copy of the rule → no inconsistency
  Sprint 12: Two copies (service + domain) → drift introduced
  Sprint 14: New code trusts domain → drift surfaces as bug
end note

@enduml
